+The Sanskrit is *stūpa*, [8] or *thūpa*; it is translated as “square tomb,” and also called a numinous shrine. It is also called *caitya*, for those without bodily bones. Since this stupa has a complete body not dispersed, it is not called a caitya. The Āgamas explain the four caitya‑sites (pronounced [9] yǐ‑qiè): the places of birth, awakening, turning the Dharma wheel, and entering extinction, where stupas are raised. This jeweled stupa is the caitya‑site of a prior Buddha’s extinction. The sutra says that the Buddha’s three bodies arise from this sutra: all Buddhas here sit at the site of awakening, all Buddhas here turn the Dharma wheel, all Buddhas here enter parinirvāṇa; [10] only this *Lotus* is the four caitya‑sites of the Buddhas of the three times. Previous Buddhas have already resided; the present Buddha now sits; future Buddhas will be the same. This stupa emerges to make this clear; the four assemblies all see it; therefore it is called the “Vision of the Jeweled Stupa” chapter. The *Yingluo Sūtra* says that Sujāti asked, “Are the merits of the living body, the whole‑body relics, and the fragmented relics equal?” The Buddha said, “Not equal. The physical body teaches and transforms; the three karmas are fully pure, and beings reach the site of awakening. Whole or fragmented relics only display numinous light; offerings gain merit. Therefore they are not equal.” He further asked the Topping‑King Tathāgata, “For twelve nayuta kalpas you preached and taught; the relics likewise should be equal.” The Buddha said, “All are produced by the supernatural power of the Topping‑King Tathāgata.” That sutra measures whole and fragmented relics as all due to the Buddha‑power of the living body; this sutra measures the living‑body relics, whole and fragmented relics, and the partial and complete relics of the Dharma‑body as all arising from this sutra, showing that this sutra’s merit and the power of upholding are great. The stupa rises from the ground [1] to prove this; the four assemblies all see it; therefore it is called the “Vision of the Jeweled Stupa” chapter. The Northern teacher says: “When the Buddha preached to Śāriputra, the jeweled stupa already appeared to certify it; if it came after the preaching, what would it certify? The compiler arranged the sequence and placed it after the three cycles.” This is merely human sentiment and cannot be trusted. Now, according to the *Sāyun‑Phundarīka Sūtra*, it says: “When the Buddha preached the Lotus for innumerable verses, a seven‑jeweled stupa emerged from the ground. Within was a golden couch; on the couch was a Buddha named Pao‑xiulānluó, in Chinese ‘Great Jewel,’ who praised Śākyamuni saying, ‘I came to make offerings. I wish to sit on my golden couch, and for me you should again preach the Sā[2]yun‑Phundarīka.’” Relying on that sutra, this proves that he had already preached the three cycles, and later again requested the lifespan. The explicit text is holy speech, yet some refused to use it; how could we accept human fabrications? This stupa precisely rises from the ground to certify the earlier and request the later; the four assemblies all see it; therefore it is called the “Vision of the Jeweled Stupa” chapter. The Northern teacher says Many‑Jewels is the Dharma‑body Buddha; the *Treatise* says Many‑Jewels is a transformation body produced by vows to certify the sutra; this text is the same. The teacher says: the Dharma‑body neither comes nor goes; the reward body is lofty and grand; the response body responds everywhere. If one takes these as the three Buddhas, one has not exhausted their substance; [＊10‑1] this is only an indication. Many‑Jewels indicates the Dharma‑Buddha, Śākyamuni indicates the reward‑Buddha, and the division bodies indicate the response‑Buddha. Though three, they are not one nor different; one should speak thus and understand thus. These four explanations are the four siddhāntas for interpreting the vision of the jeweled stupa, etc. The stupa’s emergence has two functions: first, it issues a sound to certify what precedes; second, it opens the stupa to initiate what follows. Certifying what precedes means certifying that the three cycles of preaching are all true: if stated briefly, they all accord with real‑mark; if stated broadly, they are beyond the four propositions and cut off the hundred negations; if stated from the middle, the eight negations are true. The stupa rising from the ground shows non‑extinction; dividing the seat and sitting together shows non‑birth; entering the stupa shows non‑constancy; displaying the stupa shows non‑cessation; the division bodies show not‑one; the complete body shows not‑different; Many‑Jewels yielding the seat shows not‑coming; Śākyamuni sitting on half the seat shows not‑going. The eight negations are manifest; thus it is true. It also certifies the trace‑gate circulation: the merit of holding the sutra is deep and the power of propagating it is great; all are true. “Equal great wisdom” — how does it compare to prajñā? *Treatise* 79 says, “Prajñā is the wondrous Dharma of the Buddhas of the three times; like one city gate, it is entered from the four directions.” Thus know that prajñā is also called wondrous Dharma. This sutra is called “equal great wisdom”; the two texts point to each other and the meaning can be known. Initiating what follows: if one wishes to open the stupa, one must gather the division bodies, clarify the mysterious entrustment, and with a sound reaching the lower realms summon the original disciples to discuss the lifespan. The ancient stupa rises from the ground, opening the power of自在神通 and manifesting benefit to past worlds. It issues a great sound, opening the lion’s rapid‑stride power, manifesting the present opening of the provisional and revealing of the real in the ten directions. It has a great vow: when future Buddhas preach this sutra, my jeweled stupa will come to their place to certify it, opening the great might and showing future constant non‑extinction. Moreover, the stupa in空 also certifies what precedes and initiates what follows: the seven expedient persons hide the principle, not yet opened and obscured by ignorance, like the stupa in the ground; when they hear the three cycles and open the three to reveal the real, opening Buddha‑knowledge, the Dharma‑body appears like the stupa rising into空 — this certifies what precedes. When one cultivates and the Dharma‑body has long been bright, it is like the stupa in空 that no one can open, showing the original ground long accomplished and unknown to the assembly. If one reveals traces and displays the origin and understands without doubt, that is initiating what follows. If the stupa rises from the ground, it indicates the Dharma‑body manifest; this is the same as other sutras for bodhisattvas manifesting the Dharma‑body, but different for the two vehicles manifesting the Dharma‑body. If the stupa is in空 and its door is opened to see the Buddha, it indicates revealing traces and displaying the origin, and is entirely different from other sutras. If the stupa comes to certify, the prior matters are already clear and there is no need to doubt; if the stupa comes to initiate what follows, it secretly has meaning unknown to the crowd — here we take the latter meaning in advance, and it is not blameworthy. In the contemplation‑of‑mind interpretation: by practicing contemplation in accordance with the sutra, one corresponds with the Dharma‑body and the object and wisdom must meet. When the stupa comes to certify the sutra, the object and wisdom meeting means the great retribution is complete, like Śākyamuni and Many‑Jewels sitting together on one seat. Because the great retribution is complete, responses appear according to capacities, like all the division bodies gathering; because Many‑Jewels emerges, the three Buddhas are revealed; because one upholds the sutra, one immediately possesses the three bodies. *Samantabhadra Contemplation* says, “Th