+This chapter has prose and verse. The prose has three: (1) clarifying Many‑Jewels’ emergence, (2) clarifying the distant gathering of division bodies, (3) clarifying Śākyamuni’s call to seek those who will circulate the sutra. The first text has six: (1) the stupa’s appearance, (2) the gods’ offerings, (3) Many‑Jewels’ praise, (4) the assembly’s surprise, (5) Great Joy of Preaching’s question, (6) the Tathāgata’s answer. “A stupa of seven jewels” means the ground of the Dharma‑body is endowed by nature with the seven awakening factors and the seven noble treasures; the stupa is the境 of real‑mark, the place on which the Dharma‑body depends. “Five hundred yojanas in height” is twenty thousand li, indicating vertically the ten‑thousand practices in the cause and ten‑thousand virtues in the result. “Two hundred fifty yojanas in width” is ten thousand li, indicating horizontally the ten‑thousand good qualities as adornments. “Earth” is the ground of ignorance: by having nothing to break, it breaks ignorance; by having nothing to dwell in, it dwells in first‑principle emptiness. “Various treasures” are the multitude of samādhi and wisdom as adornment. “Railings” are dhāraṇī. “Myriad niches” are the rooms of infinite compassion, also the empty houses of infinite emptiness. “Banners and pennants” are the superior marks of supernatural powers. “Strings of jeweled necklaces” are the merits of the forty stages, adorning the Dharma‑body above and benefitting beings below. “Myriads of jeweled bells” are the eight tones and four kinds of eloquence. “Fragrance issuing from the four sides” is the path‑wind of the Four Truths blowing the fragrance of the four virtues. “Rising as high as the Palace of the Four Heavenly Kings” means exhausting the principle of the Four Truths.
