+Below “Great Joy of Preaching, by the Tathāgata’s spiritual power,” second: clarifying the distant gathering of division bodies. This has seven: (1) Great Joy requests to see Many‑Jewels, (2) the Buddha should gather the division bodies, (3) Great Joy requests the gathering, (4) releasing light to summon from afar, (5) all Buddhas come together, (6) purifying the lands, (7) giving consent to open the stupa. Explaining the first request: saying “by relying on the Buddha’s spiritual power” means that to open the stupa one must gather the Buddhas; gathering the Buddhas is entrustment; entrustment is summoning the disciples below; when the disciples below emerge, the near is opened and the far revealed — this is the cause of this great matter; how could it not be the Buddha’s spiritual power that prompts the question? The remaining sections are as in the text. Below “At that time the Buddha emitted light from the white hair‑mark,” fourth: releasing light to summon from afar. The three transformations of the land are due to samādhi, and samādhi has three: the first transforms Saha, which is the back‑rejection that can transform defilement into purity; the second transforms two hundred nayutas, which is the mastery of the sphere of victory; the third transforms another two hundred nayutas, which is the all‑pervading sphere with no obstruction to its object. Again, the first transformation shows purification of the four abodes; the second shows purification of dust‑sand; the third shows purification of ignorance. “At that time the Buddhas sat on lion seats,” seventh: giving consent to open the stupa, again in five: (1) the Buddhas exchange greetings and declare consent, (2) Śākyamuni opens the stupa, (3) the four assemblies all see and hear, (4) the two Buddhas divide the seat and sit, (5) the four assemblies request empowerment. The Buddhas [5] all consent to open the stupa, like the consent in a saṅgha procedure. The *Great Collection* explains that a number of Buddhas consent; the *Huayan* also says Buddhas in the ten directions together speak the *Huayan*; the *Great Prajñā* also says a thousand Buddhas together speak the *Prajñā* — none say they are Śākyamuni’s division bodies; but according to this sutra they should be division bodies. Those sutras are provisional, so at that time they did not explicitly say so. This sutra not only has many, it also directly says they are division bodies and all come to consent. Below “At that time Śākyamuni saw,” second: opening the stupa is opening the provisional; seeing the Buddha is revealing the real; it also certifies what preceded and will open what follows. “Like unfastening a lock” means removing obstruction and moving the capacity. Below “with a great sound,” second: Śākyamuni proclaims and seeks those who will circulate the sutra. This again has three: (1) loudly proclaims the search, (2) below “The Tathāgata will not be long” clarifies the time of entrustment, (3) below “The Buddha wishes to” clarifies that the entrustment has a recipient. “Has a recipient” has two meanings: near — entrusting the eighty‑thousand and twenty‑thousand bodhisattvas who already dwell here to propagate in this land; far — entrusting the original disciples in the thousand‑world dust to propagate everywhere, and thus initiating the lifespan chapter.
