. If counted as three heinous crimes, the king‑instruction and poisoned nails are included in harming the Buddha. Because he should perform contrary deeds, when he was born humans and gods were hot‑hearted; from this he got his name, thus “heavenly heat” — this is the trace. If explained at the origin, beings have afflictions, so the bodhisattva [2] manifests heat, sharing their illness‑conduct to liberate them. The intent of this chapter is to cite ancient propagation and show its benefit is not false, to clarify that present teaching has proven efficacy, and to use the past to exhort the present to circulate it. The text has two: (1) up to “born from a lotus before the Buddha,” clarifies past Devadatta transmitting the sutra and Śākyamuni attaining Buddhahood; (2) from “at that time the bodhisattvas from below in Many‑Jewels’ place” down, clarifies present Mañjuśrī transmitting the sutra and the dragon girl becoming Buddha; if even those who receive the teaching are so, how could the benefit of propagating be not great! Therefore Devadatta receives prediction; Mañjuśrī can be known by intent (etc.).
