+Below “Telling the bhikṣus, the king...” second: concluding past and present, again in two: (1) directly concluding past and present, as in the text; (2) below “Because of Devadatta,” clarifying that both teacher and disciple’s merit and reward are complete. Within the completion there are two: first clarifying that the disciple’s causal reward is complete; second, below “The Buddha told the four assemblies,” clarifying that the Dharma‑teacher’s wondrous fruit will be accomplished. Within the disciple section there are three: first clarifying the cause completed; next, below “Thirty‑two marks,” clarifying the fruit completed; last, below “All because of Devadatta,” concluding that the benefit is due to the one who transmitted the sutra. First, “complete the six pāramitās”: the meanings of pāramitā are many. The *Great Treatise* says: abandoning the dependent and the dependent‑recompense is dāna; preventing the seven branches is precepts; being beaten and cursed without retaliation is patience; carrying things through from start to finish is diligence; the four dhyānas and eight samādhis are meditation; dividing stages and ceasing disputes is prajñā. Again, if one bundles the ten good acts into six: not killing through not lying are dāna; not double‑tongue is śīla; not harsh speech is patience; not frivolous speech is diligence; not greed and not anger are meditation; not wrong view is prajñā. The *Bodhisattva Good Precepts*, fascicle 10, says: “The six pāramitās are of three kinds: (1) as antidotes, namely to stinginess, evil, anger, laziness, chaos, and delusion (etc.); (2) as mutually generating: abandoning home and keeping precepts, meeting insult and needing patience, patience then leading to diligence, diligence then regulating the five roots, the roots regulated then knowing the dharma‑realm; (3) as fruits: wealth, color, strength, longevity, peace, and eloquence.” Other sutras say: giving yields wealth; precepts yield good destinies; patience yields uprightness; diligence yields supernatural powers; meditation yields rebirth in heaven; wisdom yields the breaking of afflictions. Such examples are the Tripiṭaka teaching’s explanation of the six pāramitās. If giving, recipient, and thing are all empty, it is called dāna; not seeing keeping or breaking is called precepts; the patient and the object of patience being unobtainable is called patience; body and mind unmoved is called diligence; not scattered and not savoring is called meditation; neither wise nor foolish is called prajñā — this pattern is the Common teaching’s six pāramitās. If one says that dāna has ten benefits: [7] subduing the stingy affliction, continuity of the giving mind, sharing resources with beings, being born in a wealthy house, in each life the giving mind appears, the four assemblies love and respect, in the crowd one is not timid, a superior name spreads everywhere, hands and feet are soft, up to reaching the site of awakening and constantly meeting good friends. Precepts have ten benefits: fulfilling all‑knowledge as the Buddha learned it, not being destroyed by the wise, vows not退, abiding in practice, abandoning birth‑and‑death and yearning for nirvāṇa, obtaining an un‑entangled mind, obtaining superior samādhi, and not lacking faith‑treasure. Patience has ten benefits: fire, blades, poison, and water cannot harm; non‑humans guard one; the body‑marks are adorned; it closes the evil paths and is born in Brahmā heaven; day and night are always at ease; the body never leaves joy. Diligence has ten benefits: others cannot subdue one; one is protected by the Buddha; non‑humans guard one; one does not forget what is heard; what is not heard can be heard; eloquence grows; one obtains samādhi‑nature; few illnesses and troubles; food is easily digested, like the uḍumbara flower’s increase. Meditation has ten benefits: abiding in proper deportment and practicing the慈境界; no remorse‑heat; guarding the faculties; obtaining joy without food; departing desire and cultivating meditation without emptiness; being freed from the māra‑net and abiding in the Buddha‑realm; liberation becomes [8] mature. Prajñā has ten benefits: not grasping the marks of giving; not relying on precepts; not abiding in patience‑power; [9] not departing body‑mind diligence; meditation has nowhere to abide and māras cannot disturb; others’ words cannot move one; one reaches the bottom of birth‑and‑death and gives rise to superior慈; one does not delight in the two‑vehicle ground. Four things should be practiced for dāna: (1) practitioners destroy stinginess; (2) to adorn bodhi; (3) self‑and‑other benefit — when one wishes to give, gives, and after giving rejoices, this is self‑benefit; when the hungry and thirsty are relieved, this is benefit to others; (4) to obtain great good fruit in future lives, gaining great honor and abundant wealth. Four things should be practiced for precepts: self‑cultivating good dharmas and extinguishing evil; precepts adorn bodhi and gather beings; in lying or waking one is at ease, has no [10] regret, and has no harmful mind toward beings; afterward one receives human and heavenly joy and nirvāṇa, etc. Four things should be practiced for patience: cultivating patience removes non‑patience; adorning bodhi and gathering beings; both sides depart fear; in future lives there is no anger, kin are not destroyed, and one does not receive suffering, gaining human and heavenly nirvāṇa‑joy. Four things should be practiced for diligence: diligence breaks laziness; adorns bodhi and gathers beings; increasing good dharmas is self‑benefit; not troubling others is benefit to others; afterward one gains great power and reaches bodhi. Four things should be practiced for meditation: meditation breaks a scattered mind; adorns bodhi and gathers beings; body and mind are tranquil as self‑benefit; not troubling beings is benefit to others; afterward one receives a pure body, is at ease, and gains nirvāṇa. Four things should be practiced for prajñā: wisdom breaks ignorance; adorns bodhi and gathers beings; wisdom‑joy is self‑benefit; teaching beings is benefit to others; it can destroy afflictions and wisdom‑obstructions and is a great fruit. Such patterns are the Distinct teaching’s six pāramitās. The *Moon‑Storehouse* (fascicle 1) says: “If beings only rely on reading and recitation to seek bodhi, they are attached to the worldly; they still cannot tame their own afflictions, how could they tame others? Such a person clings to jealousy, fame, profit, wealth, and honor, is high‑minded, self‑righteous, and lightly slanders others. They still cannot obtain wholesome roots of the desire realm, much less wholesome roots of form and formless, much less two‑vehicle bodhi, much less unsurpassed bodhi. It is like star‑fire cannot dry the sea, breath cannot move a mountain, lotus‑threads cannot weigh a peak. Why? The worldly cannot fulfill bodhi. What is the first‑principle? It is making all meritorious acts: if one cultivates body, mind, and wisdom, perfuming them with the first principle, then one quickly fulfills the six pāramitās. Whether walking or sitting, abandoning clinging thoughts is dāna; abandoning clinging and not violating is śīla; not raising sores in境界 is kṣānti; not abandoning separation is diligence; not being lax in affairs is meditation; the nature of all dharmas being unborn is prajñā. Again: regarding the skandhas, abandoning is dāna; not counting and thinking the skandhas is śīla; not‑self thoughts about the skandhas is kṣānti; raising resentment toward the skandhas is diligence; the skandhas not blazing is meditation; the skandhas being ultimately abandoned is prajñā. Regarding the realms: abandoning is dāna; not being turbulent in the realms is śīla; abandoning causal conditions in the realms is kṣānti; repeatedly abandoning in the realms is diligence; not giving rise in the realms is meditation; like幻 in the realms is prajñā. Such are called the profound dharma‑essentials of first‑principle skillful means, which can fulfill the six pāramitās.” Using this Dharma for self and others, bodhisattvas of the three times all cultivate it to achieve bodhi; therefore it is not worldly. This Dharma can still the afflictions‑path and suffering‑path of beings and place them on the bodhi path. The *Huayan* explains that on the seventh ground, in every thought one fully possesses and cultivates all Buddha‑dharmas with the ten pāramitās: seeking the Buddha‑path’s good roots for all beings is dāna; extinguishing the heat of all afflictions is śīla; not harming any beings is patience; seeking good without weariness is diligence; cultivating the path‑mind without scattering and always oriented to all‑wisdom is meditation; enduring the gate of non‑arising of all dharmas is prajñā; being able to raise immeasurable wisdom‑gates is skillful means; seeking to turn supreme wisdom is vow; māras and wrongs cannot阻 is power; speaking the marks of all dharmas as they truly are is knowledge. Because the ten pāramitās are complete, the four摄, the path factors, the three liberations, and all aids to bodhi are all complete in every thought; all grounds are complete in every thought; because this ground is superior. Such examples are the Perfect teaching’s six pāramitās.
