+From “Mañjuśrī said, I in the sea” downward, second: clarifying the benefit. The text has nine: (1) Mañjuśrī’s self‑statement, (2) Zhiji’s question, (3) answer, (4) Zhiji’s doubt based on the Distinct teaching, (5) the dragon girl clarifies the Perfect teaching to resolve doubt, (6) Śāriputra, holding the Tripiṭaka’s provisional view, raises difficulties, (7) the dragon girl uses the One‑Real to remove doubt, (8) the assembly sees and hears and gains benefit, (9) Zhiji and Śāriputra silently believe and submit. In the fifth, the dragon girl clarifies the Perfect teaching to resolve doubt: first, the sutra narrates her appearing and expressing reverence. Next there are three and a half lines of verse, in three: first half‑line clarifies understanding gained by holding the sutra; next two lines clarify accomplishing the two bodies; last line cites the Buddha as proof. “Merit and demerit”: in the seven expedients it is transmitted as such; now the verse deeply reaches no‑merit and no‑demerit entering the One‑Real, named “deep reach.” “Ten directions” are the ten dharma‑realms, all illumined by real wisdom, hence “pervading illumination.” “Complete the thirty‑two marks” means: deeply obtaining the principle of the Dharma‑body is to possess the marks, as the *Mahāprajñā* explains: if one wishes to obtain all dharmas, one should study prajñā, like obtaining a wish‑fulfilling jewel; the two vehicles only obtain emptiness, and emptiness has no marks (etc.). Sixth, Śāriputra again raises difficulties: first generally doubting, then explaining the five obstacles. Seventh, the dragon girl manifests immediate attainment to prove: again in two — first, she offers the jewel to indicate complete understanding. The round jewel shows she has cultivated the perfect cause; offering it to the Buddha is bringing cause to complete fruit; the Buddha receives it swiftly, thus the fruit is obtained swiftly; this is immediate seating at the path‑site, attainment of Buddhahood is not false. 