+Second, the exhortation to uphold has prose and verse. The prose has five: (1) the Buddha gazes with his eyes, (2) the bodhisattvas ask for instruction, (3) the Buddha is [2] silent, (4) the bodhisattvas know his intent, (5) they vow to propagate the sutra. The Buddha’s gazing and silent exhortation without spoken instruction means: above, though there was no separate command, the profound merit of holding the sutra has been lifted and proven clearly; Many‑Jewels and the division bodies came from afar to exhort and arouse; the earnestness of this matter is sufficient. Those who wish to accept the command should vow immediately without [3] repeated words; moreover, he protects the śrāvakas’ vows for other lands and thus does not praise them. The verse has twenty lines requesting protection of those who uphold the sutra; it is not further subdivided — follow the text. The first seventeen lines are about propagating the sutra by wearing the armor of patience; the next, the second, one line, is propagating by entering the room; the next, the third, one line, is propagating by sitting on the seat; the next, the fourth, one line, is a general conclusion requesting [4] empowerment. The *Middle Āgama* (fascicle 6) says, “Araṇya is translated as ‘no matters’; dhūta is translated as [5] ‘shaking off’.” The *Bao‑yun Sūtra* (fascicle 6) says, “A bhikṣu in an āraṇya place, seeing kings, princes, brahmins, and all people come, the bhikṣu chants ‘welcome, you may sit here.’ They then sit together; if they do not sit, the bhikṣu also does not sit; he should speak Dharma to gladden them.” After the Buddha’s extinction, in the final evil age, one should not be a model bhikṣu: though one speaks the precepts and obtains livelihood, one does not delight in practicing the precepts. Through the five parts of the Dharma‑body, the rest of all path‑dharmas are likewise: it is like a snuffling‑nose person speaking of sandalwood — [6] he himself has no fragrance and does not smell it himself. Gods, humans, dragons, and kumbhāṇḍas will never make offerings to a preceptless person. The remaining four parts are likewise; there is no [8] one who can bring the wondrous Dharma — it must arise from pure precepts, and the other four are likewise. If one encounters a most severe illness near death, with pain and distress pressing to the point of no [9] cure, if one constantly does not abandon the Buddha‑samādhi, all suffering cuts off the mind; because that person himself understands this Dharma, he then knows that all dharmas are empty. “Armor of patience”: the *Middle Āgama* (fascicle 5) says, “Bhikṣu Kālaka complained to the Buddha, saying, ‘Śāriputra cursed me and spoke ill of me.’ The Buddha quickly summoned Śāriputra: ‘Did you in fact curse him?’ Śāriputra said, ‘Those whose minds are unsettled may curse; my mind is settled, how could I curse? Like an ox with broken horns that does not gore, like a crippled child ashamed and not harming others, my mind is like earth, water, fire, and wind: it receives clean and unclean, large and small, feces and spittle, without cursing. My mind is like a broom: clean and unclean are both swept. Again, like a broken vessel filled with fat set in the sun, drip by drip it constantly leaks; I contemplate the nine apertures constantly leaking impurity — how could I curse others? Again, like a dead snake or dog tied around a clean child’s neck, ashamed and abashed, he does not curse others.’ The Buddha asked, ‘How do you view such evil people?’ He answered, ‘There are five kinds of persons: (1) body good, mouth and mind [10] not good — only think of their goodness and not their non‑good, like a robe‑gathering bhikṣu who sees a heap of filth and torn cloth, takes the right and left, cuts off the unclean and takes the clean, and uses the clean of his body to regulate my body, discarding his mouth and mind to warn my mouth and mind. (2) mouth conduct clean, body and mind unclean — also think of his mouth and discard his body and mind, like a hot and thirsty person who meets a grassy pond, pushes aside the grass and scoops water to cool the body and stop thirst. (3) mind clean, body and mouth unclean — also think of his mind and do not use his body and mouth, like a traveler hot and thirsty who finds only a little water in an ox‑hoofprint; if he uses a scoop or hand, it becomes muddy, so he should kneel on both knees, bring both hands to his mouth, and drink to relieve thirst. (4) all three karmas unclean — though there is nothing to use, one should pity and念 him, like seeing a sick person on the road, arranging him to be stable, thinking of his impurity so that he may meet good friends to heal his three karmas and not fall into the three bad paths. (5) all three are clean — always think of this person to instruct and compare oneself, aligning one’s thoughts and vows; like a cool pond with many flowers and grasses, the hot and thirsty enter it to revive themselves, always念 the境界 to remove my evils.’” This is the Tripiṭaka teaching using suffering, impermanence, impurity, no‑self, and emptiness as armor. The *Vibhāṣā* (fascicle 8) says: “Thinking ‘cursing’ is one word; the rest are all summons. If all day they summon, what is it to me? Again, here it is a base word, elsewhere it is a word of praise; if I念 this base word, there is nowhere I can find joy. Again, observe the word ‘curse’: if you invert the word, it becomes praise. Again, cursing is a small part of one realm, one entrance, one skandha; the cursing is small and the non‑cursing is much. Again, who accomplishes the curse? The curser accomplishes it; the accomplishment is on his side — what is it to me? Again, cursing is one word; one word does not make a curse, two words make a curse; there is no time when two words are spoken at once; if one speaks the latter word, the former has already ceased. Again, the one who curses and the one cursed are in one time, the same instant, and both cease — what is it to me?” Such is using emptiness as armor. Fascicle seventeen says: “Both ordinary and sage have three feelings. How do they differ? The ordinary have two in painful feeling: bodily pain and mental sorrow, like three poison‑arrows. Losing pleasure they become angry, gaining pleasure they rejoice, neither‑pain‑nor‑pleasure they are deluded. The sage has only bodily feeling and no mental feeling; toward pain he does not get angry, toward pleasure he does not cling, toward neither he is not deluded; the three afflictors cannot afflict him; he is liberated from the afflictors. Thus there is the difference of ordinary and sage.” Such differences of having and not having are using the Distinct teaching as armor. Now this sutra clarifies armor as “mindfulness of the Buddha is armor”: this is mindfulness of the Dharma‑Buddha of first principle; the Buddha is the Dharma. The text says: mindfulness of the Buddha and his exhortation is the Dharma; the Buddha is the saṅgha; the saṅgha is the harmony of事 and理; [1] Vairocana pervades all places. Such armor — one armor is all armors — is the Perfect teaching’s armor.
