+This chapter is explained in three: by events, by attaching to the text, and by the Dharma‑gate. By events: the body has no danger, thus “peace”; the mind has no忧惱, thus “joy”; body and mind at peace and joy, thus it can advance in practice. By attaching to the text: wearing the Tathāgata’s robe makes the Dharma‑body peaceful; entering the Tathāgata’s room makes the mind joyful in liberation; sitting on the Tathāgata’s seat means prajñā guides the practice’s advance — this is explanation attached to the previous chapter’s text. Dwelling on the ground of patience makes the body peaceful; not being sudden or violent makes the mind joyful; contemplating the real‑mark of all dharmas makes practice advance. By the Dharma‑gate: peace is “not moving,” joy is “non‑reception,” practice is “non‑practice.” Not‑moving means that birth‑and‑death of the six paths and the nirvāṇa of the two sages cannot move it; since it does not cling to the two extremes, the body has no movement. The prior text says, “Body and limbs are calm and unmoving; the mind is always still and never scattered”; thus it abides in the not‑moving gate like the peak of Sumeru. Joy means it does not receive the vast functions of samādhi, does not receive the five feelings of ordinary people; even in the Perfect teaching the five feelings that give rise to views are not received. If there is reception, there is suffering; if there is no reception, there is no suffering; no suffering and no joy is called great joy. Non‑practice: if there is reception there is practice; if no reception there is no practice — it does not practice the ordinary person’s practice, nor the sage’s practice; therefore it is called non‑practice, yet it practices the middle way; hence it is named “practice” and is the Dharma‑gate. Now further explanation by events: peaceful practice is great nirvāṇa, named from the fruit; practice is the path to nirvāṇa, named from the cause. Other causes and fruits are both suffering: the eternalist outsiders practice苦行 and obtain苦果; or the cause is pleasure and the fruit is suffering, like the annihilationist outsiders indulging pleasure and later gaining苦報; or the cause is苦 and the fruit is樂, like the analytical two vehicles with impermanent clumsy deliverance, who only enter nirvāṇa after painful exertion. Now peaceful practice is cause and fruit both joyful — this is the *Mahāprajñā*’s skillful crossing as such. The *Great Sutra* says: “Those who definitely practice苦行 are ordinary people; those who practice苦樂 are śrāvakas and pratyekabuddhas; those who definitely practice樂行 are bodhisattvas.” The seven expedients’ coarse causes and coarse fruits are all not peaceful practice; only this wondrous cause and wondrous fruit are called peaceful practice. Further explaining by the text: peaceful practice is the nirvāṇa path. Nirvāṇa has three meanings, namely the secret treasury of the three virtues; practice has three meanings, namely cessation‑practice, contemplation‑practice, and compassion‑practice. Cessation‑practice: the three karmas, gentle and compliant, are all quiet — this is the Dharma‑body practice, i.e., the Tathāgata’s robe above. Contemplation‑practice: the one real‑mark wisdom with non‑discriminating light — this is prajñā practice, i.e., the Tathāgata’s seat above. Compassion‑practice: the four vast vows widely deliver all — this is liberation practice, i.e., the Tathāgata’s room above. Gathering these three practices as the nirvāṇa path, and taking the three virtues as the境 of practice, the境 is called peaceful and the path is called practice. The *Great Treatise* says: “From first arousing the mind, the bodhisattva always contemplates nirvāṇa and practices the path; at the causal stage he uses these three practices, guiding the three karmas as practice. When the three karmas are pure, this is purity of the six roots; when the six roots are pure, a likeness‑understanding arises and one enters the real; at the fruit stage it is called the Buddha’s eyes and ears, etc.” The cause is called cessation‑practice, the fruit is called the virtue of cutting off; the cause is called contemplation‑practice, the fruit is the virtue of wisdom; the cause is compassion‑practice, the fruit is the virtue of grace. Again, the cause is three karmas, the fruit is three mysteries; in the causal stage compassion guides the three karmas to benefit others, in the fruit stage it is the three wheels of inconceivable transformation. In such contemplation there is no further discrimination: in all [2] dharmas there is peaceful‑joy nature; all beings are great nirvāṇa and cannot be further extinguished; practicing the non‑path, one通 to the Buddha‑path — this is the absolute explanation of peaceful practice, and this practice accords with nirvāṇa‑meaning. That text also says there is another practice that is the Tathāgata‑practice: the Tathāgata is the person, peaceful‑joy is the Dharma; the Tathāgata is the peaceful person, peaceful‑joy is the Tathāgata‑Dharma — in general the meaning is not different, and in distinction it is also not different. This clarifies that the quiescent‑extinction patience is the Dharma‑empty seat and the Tathāgata’s room; that text clarifies golden and silver jeweled trees — jeweled trees are the forest of non‑outflow jewels; the non‑outflow aligns with the empty quiescent‑extinction patience; the golden sand great river entering the western sea aligns with the one real wisdom and the emptiness of all dharmas; women attaining the path means no flattery or曲 — this aligns the unconditioned great [3] compassion with the Tathāgata’s room; they call it the meaning of no remainder; here it is called the unsurpassed path. Again, the meaning of the five practices also matches the robe, seat, and room.
