+In the broad explanation of Dharma‑gates, one should clarify the not‑moving gate, the non‑receiving gate, and the non‑practice gate; this is briefly not recorded. This chapter is the fourth intent of the trace‑gate circulation. If twenty‑thousand and eighty‑billion nayutas receive the command to propagate the sutra, deeply knowing provisional and real, widely knowing gradual and sudden, and also reaching capacities and conditions with自在神力, then the turbulent evils of the defiled world do not obstruct their propagation and there is no need to further show methods. But if beginners at the initial mind wish to cultivate the perfect practice and enter the defiled world to propagate, the defilement disturbs them; their self‑practice does not stand and they have no transforming功. For such persons, methods must be shown to clarify peaceful practices, therefore this chapter comes. What is the sequence of these peaceful practices? The Lotus’ perfect practice is one practice of immeasurable practices, inconceivable — how could there be fixed before and after? Now for the moment, with one thread: the “Dharma Teacher” chapter briefly shows propagation and takes benefiting others as the root, [1] first clarifying entering the room. In this chapter, discriminating evil‑world propagation and安 of逼惱, it first puts on the Tathāgata’s robe — thus the front and back mutually appear. If one speaks by the sequence of practice: all dharmas from the [2] beginning are always quiescent; if one departs quiescence and raises marks, one should first use prajñā to sweep away entanglements, thus first sit on the seat. All dharmas do not arise, yet prajñā arises; with同體 compassion for [3] beings one practices the path, next entering the Tathāgata’s room. Since compassion transforming the world must encounter compliance and opposition, one must settle in patience, next putting on the Tathāgata’s robe. Although made into this sequence, it is said not to be when practice is practiced: when practicing one enters [4] emptiness and immediately possesses all dharmas, how much more compassion and patience?
