+Regarding the four peaceful practices, the former tradition says: (1) the two emptinesses of provisional and real are the substance, (2) preaching Dharma is the substance, (3) departing faults is the substance, (4) compassion is the substance. Master Ji says: (1) emptiness, (2) departing arrogance, (3) removing jealousy, (4) great compassion. Master Long says: (1) the body keeps far from all evil and gradually approaches the principle of emptiness, (2) remove mouth‑faults, (3) remove mind‑jealousy, (4) give rise to compassion. Master Nanyue says: (1) non‑attachment right wisdom, (2) the mouth does not speak faults, (3) revering above and接 below, (4) great compassion. Master Tiantai says: cessation‑contemplation‑compassion guide the three karmas and vows. For body‑karma, because there is cessation one departs coarse bodily karma; because there is contemplation one does not obtain the body; not obtaining bodily karma is not being able to depart it; because there is no attainment one does not fall into the ordinary‑person ground. Because there is compassion one diligently cultivates bodily karma and widely benefits all, not falling into the two‑vehicle ground. Because there is cessation‑practice one wears the patience‑robe; because there is contemplation‑practice one sits on the Tathāgata’s seat; because there is compassion one enters the Tathāgata’s room. The cessation‑practice departing faults becomes the virtue of cutting off; the contemplation‑practice non‑attachment becomes the virtue of wisdom; compassion benefitting others becomes the virtue of grace. The virtue of grace supports and completes the virtue of wisdom; the virtue of wisdom can通 the virtue of cutting off. This is called the peaceful practice of body‑karma. The remaining mouth, mind, and vows are also thus.
