+二、約二法，即生、法二忍，二忍即生、法二空。二空異二乘。何者？人、法二空約真俗假實，明二空二忍悉見中道，故不同二乘。若更開者即四忍，若作五忍指善字為信忍，若作六忍指和字為和從忍；若對地即開四十二忍，一地尚有四十一地功德，一忍寧無四十一忍法耶？今且約四忍消文，謂伏、順、無生、寂滅忍[7]也。此四忍與別教異，彼前二忍是生忍，位則淺；後二忍是法忍，位則深。今圓生法悉通，四忍亦通。何者？二空理即是中道，初住修四忍入中見二空理，乃至後心亦[8]窮二空理。《大經》云「發心畢竟二不別」。若約無淺深判四忍者，從初發心圓伏五住，至金剛頂皆名伏忍；初後悉不違實相，名順忍；初後悉不起二邊心，名無生忍；初後悉休息眾行，名寂滅忍。聞生死不怱卒畏苦，聞涅槃不怱卒證樂，聞佛常與無常、二乘作佛不作佛，聞生死涅槃異與不異，聞佛道長短難易非長非短非難非易等皆不驚怖，行此行者，從始至終以二空理忍諸法，即著如來衣；安住二空理，即坐如來座；愍諸眾生，即入如來室。二空四忍名為行，理即是處，是名約二法明行處為弘經方軌也。
+
+Second: by two dharmas — the patience toward beings and the patience toward dharmas. The two patiences are the two emptinesses of beings and dharmas. The two emptinesses differ from the two vehicles. Why? The emptiness of persons and dharmas is explained via true and conventional, provisional and real, showing that the two emptinesses and two patiences all see the middle way, thus they are not the same as the two vehicles. If further opened, it becomes four patiences; if made five patiences, the善 character is taken as faith‑patience; if made six patiences, the和 character is taken as compliance‑patience. If matched to the grounds it opens into forty‑two patiences; one ground still has forty‑one grounds’功德 — how could one patience lack forty‑one patiences’ dharmas? Now, for the moment, use the four patiences to interpret the text: the patience of伏, 順, non‑arising, and quiescent‑extinction [7]. These four patiences differ from the Distinct teaching: there the first two are patience toward beings, with shallow position; the latter two are patience toward dharmas, with deep position. Now in the Perfect teaching, patience toward beings and dharmas both通; the four patiences also通. Why? The principle of the two emptinesses is exactly the middle way. At first abode one cultivates the four patiences and enters the middle, seeing the two‑emptiness principle; up to the later mind one also [8] exhausts the two‑emptiness principle. The *Great Sutra* says, “From the first arousing of mind to the end, the two are not separate.” If one judges the four patiences without shallow or deep, then from the first arousing of mind one perfectly subdues the five abodes, up to the diamond summit — all are called the patience of伏; from first to last none violates real‑mark, named the patience of順; from first to last none gives rise to two‑side mind, named the patience of non‑arising; from first to last all rest the myriad practices, named the patience of quiescent‑extinction. Hearing of birth‑and‑death, one does not abruptly fear suffering; hearing of nirvāṇa, one does not abruptly certify joy; hearing that the Buddha is constant or impermanent, that the two vehicles become or do not become Buddhas; hearing that birth‑and‑death and nirvāṇa are different or not different; hearing that the Buddha‑path is long or short, hard or easy, neither long nor short, neither hard nor easy — all these do not startle or fear. Those who practice thus, from beginning to end, use the two‑emptiness principle to endure all dharmas — this is wearing the Tathāgata’s robe; abiding in the two‑emptiness principle is sitting on the Tathāgata’s seat; pitying beings is entering the Tathāgata’s room. The two‑emptiness four‑patience is called practice; the principle is the place — this is called explaining the practice‑place by two dharmas and is the method of propagating the sutra.
