+三、約三法，三法即不思議三諦也。「住忍辱地」總論三諦，如有地可據，方能忍辱也；「柔和善順」者，善順真諦，能忍虛妄見愛寒熱等，故言善順也。「而不卒暴[1]心不驚」者，安於俗諦，忍眾根緣稱適機宜，故云不卒暴，體忍違從故心不驚也。「於法無所行」等者，即安中諦，能忍二邊，故云無所行。正住中道故云「觀實相」，亦不得中實，故云「不分別」。此則據三諦之地名處，忍五住之辱名行。行亦為三，謂止行即行不行，觀行即非行非不行，慈悲行即不行行，合上衣座舍等，是為約三法明行處，辯弘經方軌也。
+
+Third: by three dharmas — the three inconceivable truths. “Dwelling on the ground of patience” generally discusses the three truths; only with ground to rely on can one endure. “Gentle and compliant” means well complying with the true truth, able to endure false views, craving, cold and heat, etc.; thus it says gentle and compliant. “And not sudden‑violent, [1] the mind not startled” means being at ease in the conventional truth, enduring beings’ roots and conditions as suitable to the capacities; thus it says not sudden‑violent, and because one embodies patience toward compliance and opposition the mind is not startled. “With respect to dharmas, there is nothing to practice” and the like means resting in the middle truth, able to endure the two extremes; thus it says nothing to practice. Precisely abiding in the middle way, thus it says “contemplate real‑mark”; also not grasping the middle’s realness, thus it says “not discriminating.” This takes the ground of the three truths as “place,” and patience toward the five abodes as “practice.” Practice is also three: cessation‑practice is “not‑practicing yet practicing”; contemplation‑practice is “neither practice nor non‑practice”; compassion‑practice is “not‑practicing yet practicing.” These correspond to the robe, seat, and room above; thus this explains the practice‑place by three dharmas and discriminates the method of propagating the sutra.
