+「云何名近」下，第二，近處。文為三：遠十惱亂，即遠故論近，亦是附戒門助觀：修攝其心，即近故論近，亦是附定門助觀也；觀一切法空，即非遠非近論近，亦是附慧門助觀。上直緣理住忍辱地，今戒門廣出眾辱之緣應修遠離，非持刀仗亦不棄捨，但以正慧而遠離之，當知遠近廣上行所不行也。上直明不暴驚，今定門廣出修定心、修定處、修定要門，以定力故，在暴而治、在驚而安，當知即近論近，廣上不行行也。上直明無所行，今廣觀一切空具歷諸境，無量無邊無礙無障，當知非遠非近，廣上非行非不行。就初有十種應遠者：一、豪勢，二、[2]邪人法，三、兇險戲，四、[3]旃陀羅，五、二乘眾，六、遠欲想，七、遠不男，八、遠危害，九、遠譏嫌，十、遠畜養等。「路伽耶」，此云惡論，亦云破論。「逆路」者，逆君父之論。又「路」名為善論，亦名師破弟子；「逆路」名惡論，亦名弟子破師。「那羅延」者，上伎戲，亦云綵畫，其身作變異，又云緣幢擲倒之屬也。分十種為二邊：九是生死，一是涅槃，二俱遠離，即寂滅之異名耳。觀心釋十種云云，近近處有三意(云云)。[4]
+
+Below “How is it called near,” second: the near‑place. The text has three: keeping far from ten disturbances — speaking of near by way of far, also attaching to the precepts gate to aid contemplation; cultivating and gathering the mind — speaking of near by way of near, also attaching to the samādhi gate to aid contemplation; contemplating all dharmas as empty — speaking of near as neither far nor near, also attaching to the wisdom gate to aid contemplation. Above, one directly relies on principle and dwells on the ground of patience; now, through the precepts gate, the many conditions of辱 are broadly stated as to be kept far from. It is not that one holds刀仗 and does not abandon them, but that one uses correct wisdom to stay far from them — know that the far and near broadly extend the above “practice of not‑practicing.” Above it directly clarified not being sudden‑violent or startled; now the samādhi gate broadly gives cultivating the samādhi mind, cultivating the samādhi place, and cultivating the essential gate of samādhi; by the power of samādhi one can be among violence and still govern, among startling and still be calm — know that speaking of near by way of near broadly extends the above “not‑practicing yet practicing.” Above it directly clarified nothing to practice; now it broadly contemplates all emptiness and traverses all境, measureless, boundless, unobstructed, without障 — know that speaking of near as neither far nor near broadly extends the above “neither practice nor non‑practice.” In the first there are ten things to keep far from: (1) powerful influence, (2) [2]邪 persons and dharmas, (3) dangerous plays, (4) [3] caṇḍālas, (5) assemblies of the two vehicles, (6) desire‑thoughts, (7) hermaphrodites, (8) harm and danger, (9) slander and suspicion, (10) keeping livestock, etc. “Lokāyata” is translated “evil doctrines,” also “destructive doctrines.” “Inverse road” means doctrines that oppose ruler and parents. Again, “road” can mean good doctrine, also “teacher refutes disciple”; “inverse road” means evil doctrine, also “disciple refutes teacher.” “Nārāyaṇa” means upper‑level tricks and戏, also “painted transformation,” also those who climb poles and throw themselves down, etc. Dividing the ten kinds into two extremes: nine are birth‑and‑death, one is nirvāṇa; both extremes are to be kept far, which is simply another name for quiescent‑extinction. The contemplation‑of‑mind explains the ten kinds, etc.; the near‑near place has three meanings (etc.). [4]
